<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF110-370-236  </DOCNO><DOCID>10 370 236.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Today's Office  Sept 1990 v25 n4 p52(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Accessories can civilize your pc.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cody, Angela.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A host of accessories are available to make a microcomputer easieror more comfortable to use, provide better security, save space,guard against damage from static electricity, and enable the userto effect simple repairs.andP;  Some accessories address more than oneneed: copy-holders for example, put documents at eye level, makingit more comfortable to use the computer; at the same time theysave desk space.andP;  Other items that save space include componentstands and keyboard drawers.andP;  User comfort, which is directlycorrelated to productivity, is addressed by such items asfootrests, back supports and adjustable keyboards.andP;  Antistaticmats and grounding cords eliminate static electricity, which candamage hardware, software and media.andP;  Toolkits, consisting ofdemagnetized tools, allow the user to tighten screws, changecables or perform simple upgrades.andP;  Security devices are availablethat allow the micro and its peripherals to be secured to a deskor wall.andP;  Prices for these accessories range from as low as $10 upto a few hundred dollars.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersComputer AccessoriesProductivityHardware SelectionPeripherals.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>